column168: PART VI-DESCRIPTION OF EVENTS AND PACKAGE FAILURE THE KA BULK TRANSPORT, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER DIESEL FUEL INTO THE CUSTOMER’S STORAGE TANK. column168: On April 1, 2015 at 04:25 hours, personnel at CSXT Stanley Yard discovered PLMX 137047, a residue UN 1077, Propylene tank car to have a butane-like odor and a slight hissing noise coming from the protective housing with no evidence of product that could be seen.  The car was isolated and the Shipper, Braskem America, Inc. was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2015040100031.  A CSX Emergency Response contractor, Sunpro, Inc., the Toledo Branch office was dispatched to the scene. Upon inspection it was determined the vapor valve was partially open.  As a preventative measure the response team tightened the valve which stopped the leak.  The crew supervisor utilized the four-gas meter and noted that the VOC reading was 0 ppm.    Cause Code: 311 at 5 points  NARRI: 5 (4 + 5 + 0) x (2 + 0) = 90

column168: On April 2, 2015, Heritage Environmental Services, Kansas City, Missouri loaded a van trailer of non-bulk flammable liquid containers.  The trailer was taken to the Butler Transfer facility in Kansas City, Kansas that same day by Heritage Transport.  On April 6, 2015 Heritage Transport driver arrived at Butler Transfer facility in Kansas City, Kansas to pick up the van to deliver it to its final destination.  Upon arrival, the driver noticed material leaking from the trailer.  He immediately notified an emergency coordinator at the Heritage Environmental Services, Kansas City, Missouri office, who gathered supplies and mobilized to the transfer station in Kansas City, Kansas.  A 55-gallon metal drum had a small hole on the side and was leaking slowly.  It appears that the forks of a fork-truck poked a hole in the side of the container, probably during the trailer loading process on April 2, 2015.  Floor dry was used to absorb the spilled material on the floor of the trailer and on the asphalt beneath the trailer.  Spill clean-up material was containerized and will be properly disposed of.  The leaking container was overpacked.  The lowest reportable quantity of the material was 10 pounds and the estimated loss of material was approximately 10 pounds.  No injuries or no property damage resulted from this incident.  No bodies of water or soil were impacted by this incident.
column169: Employee training will be conducted to review the incident and help prevent re-occurrance.

column168: During a routine walk through inspection at the Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. in-transit storage facility at Lake Point, UT a leaking drum was discovered. The drum was discovered to have a damaged area at the bottom weld/seam resulting in a release of material. Facility management was notified and an in house crew responded. The response crew donned the proper PPE, over-packed the damaged drum and clean up debris into a suitable salvage drum, and secured the drum for continued transportation to the intended disposal facility. The Utah Department of Environmental Quality was notified. Operator “Kim” provided UDEQ report # 12162.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation no evidence of leaking was observed. The shipper was advised of the incident and was requested to inspect all drums in current inventory for any containers with suspect integrity. The shipper has also been advised to use the proper liquid rated drum for waste streams with free liquids. The driver was re-instructed to perform a thorough inspection of all containers prior to accepting them for transportation and to reject or over pack containers with suspect integrity into suitable salvage drums.

column168: ENVIRITE OF PENNSYLVANIA DRIVER, WAS RETURNING TO THE ENVIRITE FACILITY LOCATED IN YORK, PA WITH A 25 CUBIC YARD ROLL-OFF BOX OF MANIFESTED HAZARDOUS WASTE (WASTE TRACKING NUMBER 013593136JJK) FROM THE GENERATOR INDUSTRIAL METAL PLATING LOCATED IN READING, PA. AS HE SLOWING DOWN IN THE RIGHT LANE OF ROUTE 30 WEST APPROACHING THE STOP LIGHT AT TORONITA STREET A CAR CUT IN FRONT OF HIS VEHICLE FROM THE LEFT LANE. THE DRIVER HAD TO BRAKE TO AVOID HITTING THE VEHICLE. IN THE PROCESS OF HARD BRAKING, THE WASTE MATERIAL SPILLED OUT THE FRONT FROM BENEATH THE TARP OF THE ROLL-OFF CONTAINER SPILLING ONTO THE ROADWAY. THE DRIVER SAFELY PULLED OFF TO THE BERM OF THE ROADWAY AND CONTACTED BEN SMITH, TRANSPORTATION MANAGER, TO REPORT THE INCIDENT AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 PM. THREE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM TEH FACILITY WERE IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL WITH 30 GALLON DRUMS AND 40 POUND BAGS OF ABSORBENT MATERIAL.    UPON EMERGENCY PERSONNEL ARRIVING AT THE SCENE, IT WAS DETERMINED TO HAVE BEEN AN APPROXIMATE 200 POUNDS OF LIQUID MATERIAL THAT SPILLED ONTO THE PUBLIC ROADWAY.  REPORTABLE QUANTITY FOR A F019 LISTED WASTE IS 10 POUNDS. EHS MANAGER, KARLA MERCER, BEGAN MAKING THE APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATIONS TO THE AGENCIES (SPILL REPORT AND NOTIFICATION FORM SUBMITTED TO PA DEP ATTACHED).    A CREW OF FOUR PERSONNEL BEGAN CLEAN-UP OF THE SPILL IN THE RIGHT LANE OF ROUTE 30 WEST. AT 4:18 PM, NOAH NIEDERERR, PA DEP SOLID WASTE SPECIALIST AND EMERGENCY RESPONDER, ARRIVED ON SCENE AND NOTED THE CLEAN UP OPERATIONS TO BE SUFFICIENT.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND ABSORBENT WAS COLLECTED IN 9 30-GALLON DRUMS AND TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE ENVIRITE FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL.    TOTAL HOURS FOR SPILL RESPONSE FROM NOTIFICATION TO COMPLETION WAS 1 1/2 HOURS.    4/2/15 @ 4:36 PM RECEIVED A FOLLOW-UP PHONE CALL FROM NOAH NIEDERERR. HE STATED HE WENT TO THE INCIDENT SITE AND APPROVED THE CLEAN UP TO BE SUFFICIENT.
column169: THE MATERIAL WHEN PICKED UP AT THE GENERATOR SITE WAS IN A SOLID FORM, HOWEVER, IN TRANSPORTATION, THE MATERIAL STRATIFIED AND A LIQUID LAYER FORMED ON TOP OF THE SLUDGY SOLID BENEATH. THE GENERATOR HAS BEEN CONTACTED TO REVIEW THEIR DEWATERING PROCESS. RECOMMENDATION HAS BEEN MADE TO EITHER PRODUCE A PROPERLY DEWATERED FILTER CAKE OR SHIP THE MATERIAL VIA TANKER PRIOR TO THE FILTRATION PROCESS. ENVIRITE WILL CONTINUE TO EVALUATE THE PHYSICAL STATE OF THE MATERIAL FOR SAFE SHIPMENT PRIOR TO TRANSPORTATION. IF NO CHANGES ARE MADE TO THE GENERATOR'S PROCESS, THEN ENVIRITE WILL CEASE THE TRANSPORTATION OF THIS MATERIAL.

column168: On April 4, 2015 at 0926 hours personnel in the CSX Pinoca Yard discovered UTLX 211057 a loaded tank car of Alcohol N.O.S leaking from the pressure relief device. The car was isolated and Renewable Product Marketing Group LLC was notified CHEMTREC Report # 2015-0404-00060.  CSX Hazmat Manager Harry Hopes was dispatched to the scene and found that the pressure relief device valve stem is broken. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Kevin Brim Phone Number 515-835-1134. The shipper was advised that pressure relief device would need to be repaired by a mobile repair unit such as RESCAR or an OTMA - 3 would be required to move the car. This incident did not require a special switching move.      NAR Cause Code: 420 Broken Cracked    2(5+3+0) X (2+0) = 32 NARRI

column168: On 04/09/2015 at 0929 hours personnel in the Norfolk Southern (Cosgrove Yard) discovered GATX 5866, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid leaking from the top (Fill hole).   The car was isolated and Southern States Chemical and South Carolina DHEC were notified. Chemtrec report #2015-04-09-00095. HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor was dispatched to the scene and found that the Fill hole had a kinked gasket allowing product to leak out of. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (John). HEPACO personnel fixed the problem and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. The incident did not require a special switching move.      NAR - Cause Code: 232 - Fill Hole    5 (3+5+1) X  (2+0) = 90 NARRI

column168: Shipment under AWB217-47436815 51pcs/492kg UN2800, Batteries, wet, non-spillable, Class 8, 51 Fibreboard Boxes X 9.50kg, Packing Instruction 872, from BKK to LAX on flight, TG692/11April 2015. Loaded in ULD number AKE91670TG. Upon breakdown of the container at about 0630am, 12 April, at the Thai Cargo warehouse, 1 box of the above shipment was found tipped on its side and apparently leaking (box appeared wet and "crushed"). Damaged box was removed and loaded upright(it stopped leaking), separated from the other cargo in the warehouse DGR area. Four boxes from three other shipments were wet from the leaking box. warehouse staff cleaned up the spill but two boxes(paper wrapped and cardboard) were wet from the battery acid.  All the affected customers were informed of the leaked material (battery acid). Only one customer rejected their package (magazines).  The damaged DGR box was not braced within the container to prevent tipping (all DGR boxes had orientation arrow markings). The box appeared to be crushed on one end but this may have been as a result of the fiberboard being soaked and deformed by the weight of the battery.  I called FAA Special Agent, Security and Hazardous Material Safety, Karen Yoneda, on 13April who came to the warehouse to inspect the damaged box.  The battery was unpacked from the outer 4G box and inner "retial" fiberboard box.  There were no apparent signs of damage(cracks, holes,separation) to the battery. The top of the battery was still wet around the filler caps. The acid level was about 1.5 inches below the "low fluid" level mark on the battery(there was still acid in all the cells).
column169: All DGR boxes must be loaded to prevent shifting or tipping during ground and air transport.  This may require bracing and blocking using straps, shrink wrap, or other braced cargo, etc.

To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released. column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: While in transit an SK driver was informed that there was a material leaking from the back of his Box Truck.  The driver immediately pulled over off the road to check his load and to verify something was leaking.  The driver found a 5 gallon pail tipped over laying on its side.  The lid was still on the container and the cap was tightly closed on the lid.  The driver placed sorbent material on the floor of the truck and drove directly to his facility.  The truck was offloaded and the remainder of the spilled area was cleaned up. Further investigation into the cause of the spill found the pail had a split in the body of the container. Both the container and the sorbent material were off loaded at the SK facility and properly disposed.  This waste was shipped from a CESQG and did not have a Uniform Hazardoius Waste Manifest accompany the shipment.

While loading drums onto a van trailer, an employee operating a forklift crossed the dock plate which had a little rise on it.  This caused the pallet to move on the forks.  A rib on the pallet cracked, causing a drum to fall into the floor of the trailer.  The drum became deformed on contact with the trailer floor.  This caused a seperation between the drum and the lid causing roughly fifteen gallons of material to spill into the trailer.  A small amount leaked through the trailer floor onto the pavement below.  The spill was immediately addressed with the drum being over packed and all liquids absorbed and containerized.  All spill related matierials were packaged for shipment to the intended hazardous waste management facility
column169: Train operators to inspect pallets for possible defects before attempting to load and ensure drum lids are secure and drums are properly positioned on pallets prior to loading.

The contractor departed with the 55-gallon drum of waste for proper disposal.

column168: A Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. tractor and tank trailer entered the Van Meter, Iowa DOT inspection site on I-80 EB at mm 115. The DOT officer instructed our driver to park and prepare the vehicle for a level 1 inspection. Upon approaching the vehicle the DOT officer detected an odor coming from tank trailer unit sr8536. The driver and officer checked the vehicle and found the top center hatch to be leaking vapor. Upon inspection the gasket was discovered to be damaged. The DOT officer placed the vehicle out of service pending repair. A mobile mechanic was called to the site to replace the defective gasket.   The Iowa Department of Natural Resources was advised of the release. Duty officer Bill Gross provided report # 041615-1320.
column169: At the time tanker sr8536 was loaded for transportation no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. The defective gasket was removed and replaced at the site prior to the vehicle being permitted to proceed. The driver has been counselled on performing and documenting a thorough vehicle and equipment inspection prior to initiating transportation activities. The driver will also receive retraining on vehicle inspections per company policy TC7.0 Driver Pre and Post Trip Inspections.

column168: Florida Rock and Tank Lines driver stared a flow and immediately realized he had not hooked to the tank and stopped shut the flow back off. Approximately 20 gallons of premium gas was released onto the pavement. The fuel ran across from the drop and puddled up agains a cement curb where it began runnign towards 58th street. The driveway on the 58th street side has a grated catch basin and although driver placed pads and began to make a dam of dirt around the basin some fuel ran into this catch basin. The fuel in the catch basin was absorbed by the debris and leaves that had collected there. St Pete Fire Dept responed and posted a fire watch. Once any free standing liquid had been absorbed with oil dry the FD cleared the scene. FL Rock dispatched SWS environmental who treated the area with absorbent and Portland Cement. SWS removed the grates and collected all impacted debris from the catch basin. All contaminated dirt and clean up materials were recoverd and removed by SWS
column169: Florida Rock and Tank Lines has taken appropriate action against the driver.

column168: A box truck containing hazardous waste arrived at the safety Kleen Eagan, MN facility for an offload in order to transfer and consolidate waste onto a van trailer to be shipped to the intended waste disposal facility. Safety Kleen Eagan, MN facility personnel noticed that there was one leaking cubic yard container. A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the truck and unloaded the leaking cubic yard container. The cubic yard container was repacked into drums for continued transportation to the final disposal facility. The box truck floor was cleaned with a cleaning compound and returned to service. The release was reported to the Minnesota Polution Control Agency. Duty officer #08 'Larry' provided report # 149513.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or breakage was observed. This release was the direct result of improper container selection and preparation. The driver will be retrained on proper container selection for solid and liquid waste streams. The shipper was notified and advised to use an appropriate UN rated container for future shipment of this waste stream.

column168: A vehicle operated by Safety-Kleen Systems was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation, it was discovered that approximately 2 gallons of material had  escaped from a pinhole leak that had developed in the container. Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised  container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and  placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and during required load checks.  Drivers will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. Drivers have been retrained in standard operating practices in drum inspection.  IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required specifications.

column168: While loading a shipment of hazardous waste onto an outbound trailer at the intermediate truck transfer facility, a drum slipped off of a pallet, striking the forklift blade.  The plastic drum was punctured and approximately 5 gallons of sludge dumped onto the concrete dock.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and overpacked the drum using a suitable salvage drum.  The material was also cleaned up from the dock and the area cleaned with a cleaning compound.  All cleanup materials were placed into the drum.  The shipment was then loaded onto the outbound trailer without further incident.
column169: The forklift driver was not following procedures while handling the drum which caused it to fall.  Driver will be retrained and disciplinary action will take place.

column62: Misaligned Material, Component, or Device; Rollover Accident
column168: Cargo Tank Motor Vehicle was maneuvering into the plant when the right trailer tandems slipped towards the ditch causing cargo content to shift. This resulted in the tractor and trailer slowly rolling over onto its right side.     The ditch was diked with sand bags and absorbent booms because the rear washout wash out cap gasket was leaking. Approximately 5 gallons of material was captured in a bucket. An additional 5 gallons of material spilled during the installation and use of a BETTS VALVE that was placed over the wash out cap to facilitate offloading of content.    Approximately 1 to 2 inches of impacted soil was removed and properly disposed of by OMI Environmental Solutions. The duration of the event from start of incident to completion of response effort was 10 hours.
column169: The root cause of the incident was driver error. A contributing factor involved the standing rain water that obstructed the drivers view of the ditch bank and associated slippery conditions.    The details of this incident will be used in new hire training curriculum and safety meeting discussions to minimize the possibility of future occurrence. Additionally, Smith System Driver training will be added to core curriculum for all drivers.

INJURIES TO SKIN AND EYES." SINCE THE BOX DID NOT HAVE ANY HAZARDOUS MARKINGS OR A MSDS ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX THE RESPONDER CALLED THE HAZMAT SUPPORT CENTER AND INFORMED THEM OF THE SITUATION. column169: Provide remedial training to material handlers to ensure they utilize safe and acceptable forklift driving techniques to recognize and prevent in the future.

column168: Our driver conducted periodic stops and checked the dome lid and other items associated with his truck.  He was approximately 1 block from his delivery point and the traffic light changed to red and he was forced to make a hard stop.  He did not realize a product leak occurred until the pickup truck pulled in behind him and the driver of the pickup showed our driver the drops of product on his vehicle.  Our driver returned to the area, however he could not detect any spillage on the road surface.     Our driver checked the dome lid on top and discovered the gasket had been pushed forward during the hard stop when the product rushed forward in the tank compartment.    We had the trailer washed and repaired.  Our company has ordered and will replace all front dome lids with a modified dome lid that is smaller.  This will allow for inspections with reduced incidents during transportation.
column169: Replacement of front dome lid with a modified dome lid that is smaller and with an improved gasket system.  This process with begin on or around 15 May 2015.

column168: The driver loaded approximately 160 barrels of product at the loading facility in Nixon, TX.  After loading, he proceeded down Highway 87 toward the intended destination in Houston, TX.  Within 1.5 miles of the loading facility, the driver braked for a stop sign and the product "sloshed" inside the trailer, exiting washout ports on the top of the trailer and spilling on to the street in the intersection.  The driver pulled the truck and trailer into an adjacent parking lot and notified appropriate authorities.  The Nixon Fire Department and Police Department responded and shut down the intersection as vehicles had driven through the spill and tracked the product along the roadway.  The Nixon Fire Department also notified the Texas Commission on Environmental Quality (which did not respond as the material did not enter a storm drain or waterway and was contained on the roadway.)  The Sun Coast Resources internal spill team responded to the scene and placed absorbent material on the roadway to clean up the spill.  A street sweeper was used to cleanup the material which will be recycled as appropriate through a third party vendor.  It was determined upon investigation that the washout ports on the top of the trailer had not been properly secured after a recent servicing by a third party vendor.
column169: Sun Coast has established a new procedure for reviewing trailers and trucks after they are returned from servicing by third party vendors.  The vendor in this case has been put on notice that they are to secure any washout port covers prior to releasing the equipment back to Sun Coast.  Sun Coast staff will now carefully inspect the equipment after it is returned from the vendor to ensure it has been properly secured prior to returning the equipment back into service.  Drivers are then required to conduct a thorough pre-trip inspection of all equipment to ensure it is road-worthy (including washout port securement) prior to leaving the facility.

column168: On April 9, 2105 the assigned driver was traveling south on US 385 in Crane County, Texas en route to a company storage facility in McCamey, TX.  The driver was operating a one-ton Chevrolet pickup towing a gooseneck flatbed trailer.  At the moment the vehicles were 5 miles south of Crane, Texas. At approximately 2:30 pm (1430 hours). The driver stated he heard a loud sound and felt the trailer not pulling as it normally should based on his experience.  The driver stated he looked in his right outside rear view mirror and noticed what appeared to be a tire disintegrating and coming apart.  The driver immediately pulled over to the right off the roadway and came to a stop.  The driver exited his vehicle and proceeded towards the right side of the trailer towards the axles. The driver stated that before reached the tire, he immediately noticed smoke coming from the tire and axles area.  He wasn't sure of the specific source of the smoke.  The driver immediately returned to the truck, obtained the required fire extinguisher and returned to the axle area.  As he did the driver stated that a fire had already started and he attempted to extinguish the flames.  He was unable to extinguish the flames.  The motorist of a passing vehicle stopped and also assisted in attempting to extinguish the flames also.  It was at this time the driver contacted Crane County 911 Services. The assisting motorist was also unsuccessful.  By this time the flames had grown and began to engulf the IBC's that contained the flammable liquids.  The IBC's were UN 31HA1 composites with a metal outer steel body with a rigid plastic inner receptacle.  The IBC's each had a 330 gallon capacity and there was a total of four (4). There were also a total of twelve (12) 5-gallon pails. The flames began to melt the plastic therefore compromising the integrity of the packages. The driver stated the trailer was completely engulfed in  flames and as the IBC's were be melted, flammable liquid product began spilling off the trailer deck and onto the ground.  The driver stated he was unable to disconnect the truck from the trailer due to the proximity of the flames and the risk of personal injury. The product that was releasing onto the ground also ignited and damaged a pipe fence. There were not any creeks, streams, river or any other bodies of water within the vicinity.  Being that the driver had no further means to extinguish the fire he began the process of stopping oncoming traffic from both directions in attempt to prevent harm to others. The driver was located on the south side of the vehicles when the first law enforcement unit arrived.  During this time the Crane Fire Department arrived on the scene from the north.  Afterwards fire department and law enforcement stated the driver did an exceptional job at controlling the scene, directing traffic and protecting others.  Arriving on the scene as WadeCo representatives were Brandon Blau and Kyle Johnson.  Also eventually arriving on the sc
column169: The incident was discussed in detail with all drivers and warehouse personnel during the safety meeting within 2 weeks afterwards.  The need to ensure all IBC's are in good condition and within the 2.5 year test and re-test requirements.  To ensure that all IBC's and other authorized packages are free of residue on the outside of the packages.  Drivers are to continue to inspect their vehicle tires as part of the pre-trip process and each time before starting a new hazmat transport.  A review was being conducted to determine if there had been similar incidents of tire failure with the same brand or tire to establish if a pattern was occurring.

column168: On April 9, 2105 the assigned driver was traveling south on US 385 in Crane County, Texas en route to a company storage facility in McCamey, TX.  The driver was operating a one-ton Chevrolet pickup towing a gooseneck flatbed trailer.  At the moment the vehicles were 5 miles south of Crane, Texas. At approximately 2:30 pm (1430 hours). The driver stated he heard a loud sound and felt the trailer not pulling as it normally should based on his experience.  The driver stated he looked in his right outside rear view mirror and noticed what appeared to be a tire disintegrating and coming apart.  The driver immediately pulled over to the right off the roadway and came to a stop.  The driver exited his vehicle and proceeded towards the right side of the trailer towards the axles. The driver stated that before reached the tire, he immediately noticed smoke coming from the tire and axles area.  He wasn't sure of the specific source of the smoke.  The driver immediately returned to the truck, obtained the required fire extinguisher and returned to the axle area.  As he did the driver stated that a fire had already started and he attempted to extinguish the flames.  He was unable to extinguish the flames.  The motorist of a passing vehicle stopped and also assisted in attempting to extinguish the flames also.  It was at this time the driver contacted Crane County 911 Services. The assisting motorist was also unsuccessful.  By this time the flames had grown and began to engulf the IBC's that contained the flammable liquids.  The IBC's were UN 31HA1 composites with a metal outer steel body with a rigid plastic inner receptacle.  The IBC's each had a 330 gallon capacity and there was a total of four (4). There were also a total of twelve (12) 5-gallon pails. The flames began to melt the plastic therefore compromising the integrity of the packages. The driver stated the trailer was completely engulfed in  flames and as the IBC's were be melted, flammable liquid product began spilling off the trailer deck and onto the ground.  The driver stated he was unable to disconnect the truck from the trailer due to the proximity of the flames and the risk of personal injury. The product that was releasing onto the ground also ignited and damaged a pipe fence. There were not any creeks, streams, river or any other bodies of water within the vicinity.  Being that the driver had no further means to extinguish the fire he began the process of stopping oncoming traffic from both directions in attempt to prevent harm to others. The driver was located on the south side of the vehicles when the first law enforcement unit arrived.  During this time the Crane Fire Department arrived on the scene from the north.  Afterwards fire department and law enforcement stated the driver did an exceptional job at controlling the scene, directing traffic and protecting others.  Arriving on the scene as WadeCo representatives were Brandon Blau and Kyle Johnson.  Also eventually arriving on the sc

Drivers are to continue to inspect their vehicle tires as part of the pre-trip process and each time before starting a new hazmat transport. column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE TRAVELING, A ROLLOVER RESULTED IN THE LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 367.5 GALLONS OF CRUDE OIL. FREE PRODUCT RELEASED TO THE ROADSIDE DITCH AND NEARBY STREAM. WEST VIRGINIA STATE POLICE RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE, ALONG WITH THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT. ERGON TRUCKING DEPLOYED A RESCUE TANKER TO RECOVER REMAINING FREE PRODUCT FROM THE DAMAGED TANKER.  HAZ-TECH ENVIRONMENTAL WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. UPON ARRIVAL ON SITE, HAZ-TECH ENVIRONMENTAL PLACED ABSORBENT BOOM DOWNSTREAM TO PREVENT FURTHER MIGRATION, AND UTILIZED A VACUUM TRUCK TO RECOVER THE FREE PRODUCT FROM THE IMPACTED AREA. ALL FREE PRODUCT AND RESIDUALS WERE RECOVERED, AND WASTE WAS TRANSPORTED OFF SITE, PENDING DISPOSAL IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. WEST VIRGINIA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION RESPONDED TO ASSESS AND OVERSEE CLEANUP ACTIVITIES. ABSORBENT BOOM WAS LEFT IN PLACE, TO CATCH RESIDUAL PRODUCT, TO BE RECOVERED FOLLOWING ANTICIPATED RAINFALL. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED, AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE.

column168: Material was being transported in totes with (8) in the nose of the trailer and (6) on the tail of the trailer for weight distribution. The driver of the unit had to slow quickly and the material on the tail of the trailer broke through the strap used to secure them and slid into the totes on the nose of the trailer. The metal cage on one of the totes punctured the plastic tote causing a leak in the trailer, unknown to the driver. Another commercial driver informed our driver that there was a chemical smell coming from our trailer, at which point our driver entered the rest area near Kannapolis, NC. around Exit 60 on I-85N.  Upon entering the rest area and exiting the truck, our driver opened the trailer to find that the totes had shifted and caused a leak.    Once the leak was found, the driver contacted his dispatch, which notified the Transportation Director and the Safety/Compliance Manager. Once notification was received, a call for emergency response was made.

During transit,it was identified that 1-330 gallon steel tote of UN1993 Flammable liquids was having an issue with a loose closure and released an estimated 5 gallons to the trailer floor. A contractor was dispatched and was able to tighten the tote so that the tote could be sent onto the consignee. The contractor utilized shop rags to absorb the minimal release and sent them to be washed and recycled versus disposing of them.
Undeclared hazmat was found during screening. Local FAA hazmat agents were notified.

Driver setting up to pull sample. When he pulled the cap off  product started to flow. Both the internal valve and external valve was open. He immediately closed the internal valve. Driver failed to check to make sure all the valves were closed before pulling the cap off. I spoke with the unloader,  Dan’l Bruner, he said he’s estimating 100-150 gallons spilled. Spill was contained and drained to their “wet well” that is pumped to a waste water treatment plant.

Tank car NATX 37282 in the railyard was reported dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) area. A containment pool was placed under NATX 37282 to capture the drippage. BNSF mechanical responders reported that the leak source was at the BOV's mounting flange connection and efforts to stop the drips were not successful. NATX 37282 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard with containment under it while awaiting commodity transfer. Commodity within NATX 37282 was transferred into another suitable tank car without further incident by 2350 hrs. PDT, 4/08/2015.

column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Stub Sill Separation from Tank (Tank Cars)
column168: On April 7th, 2015 at 09:05 hours, personnel in the Selkirk Yard discovered GATX 90784 a residue tank car of sodium hydroxide solution, UN1824 to have coupler bypass damage and the A-end stub sill bent down and torn with a release of residual product dripping from under the jacket and insulation, the class track was isolated, local and federal agencies were notified and CHEMTREC was notified, report 2015-04-07-00084, consignee and owner of the tank car, Olin Corporation of Niagara Falls, NY where notified, J. Gabryelski cell was updated on the incident and product release from GATX 90784. A CSX emergency response contractor was dispatched, EP+S of Vermont, Inc., responded to secure and contain the residual product release, it was determined that the A-end tank shell was torn at the base of the head block connection, there is a longitudinal tear through the bolster mounting pad and tank shell, approximately 16 inches in length by 2 inches in width (see attached photos), the impacting car GNWR 9003 is a loaded covered hopper car of sodium chloride (salt), the GNWR 9003 will have a complete inspection of the truck assemblies to determined a cause of the over-speed at the master and group retarders.  Olin Corporation contact John Gabryelski was updated on the complete damage of the tank car, and the tear in the tank shell.    Primary Cause Code: M407  Automatic hump retarder failed to sufficiently slow car due to foreign matter on wheels of car being humped (GNWR 9003).

column168: A FRA Hazardous Material Inspector inspecting a BNSF inbound unit PCO train (U-EPPCXP0-26T) in the railyard reported entrained tank car STAX 20037 leaking commodity from its manway closure. STAX 20037 was carefully set-out from this train and isolated in the railyard for further securement inspection and spillage cleaning. Contract responders reported the manway securement eyebolt nuts were tool tight; but the installed gasket in the manway cover groove was slightly damaged, thus not providing a good manway closure seal. column168: The employee was making a delivery to a commercial customer. Because it takes a long time to fill the tank and the customer has complained about the smell from the fixed liquid level gauge the employee did not turn it on. The employee was measuring the fill using the gauge on the end of the tank, the employee got distracted for a while, and then realized he had filled it to 90%. The employee immediately shut off the truck and detached the hose. The employee checked all the valves and gauges and everything looked ok. The employee advised his supervisor of what had happened. About 20 minutes later the customer called and stated that there was propane coming out one of the relief valves. The valve was functioning properly. The customer began pumping down their tank. They pumped it down to 70%. The relief valve eventually reseated. Both relief valves have since been replaced as precautionary measure.
column169: The employee has since went through his module 5 and skills level 2 retraining.

Tank car GATX 205431 in the railyard was reported emanating an odor. GATX 205431 was cordoned-off in the railyard. Contract responders inspecting GATX 205431 reported no odors or vapors detected from ground level surrounding GATX 205431. The responders noted the applied manway nozzle gasket was protruding from GATX 205431's manway closure. No liquid commodity spillage was observed. The applied manway nozzle gasket was crimped/deformed and it was removed. A new manway nozzle gasket was installed and the manway closure was properly secured. Seal BNSF 431252 was applied at the manway closure. Air monitoring continued through-out the manway gasket installation and manway securement completion with no detectable vapors measured at ground level. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. The valve housing/protective housing cover was sealed with BNSF 431252 seal. Response was concluded by 1615 hrs. CDT, 4/11/2015.

column168: EMPLOYEE WAS DRIVING TRUCK #4101 WHILE PULLING TRAILER #1362, HEADING NORTH BOUND ON 136TH AVE SW OF BELFIELD, ND, AFTER LOADING AT SFTU 5-19 LEASE. THE EMPLOYEE REPORTS THAT HE HAD MISJUDGED HOW CLOSE THE TRUCK WAS THE SOFT EDGE OF THE ROADWAY. THE EMPLOYEE BEGAN TO FEEL THE TRUCK PULLING HARD TOWARD THE RIGHT SIDE ROAD DITCH, IT HAD BEEN RAINING THE PREVIOUS DAY AND THE SHOULDER WAS TOO SOFT. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO BRING THE TRUCK BACK TO THE ROADWAY BUT THE TRAILER HAD TRAVELED INTO THE DITCH, UNCOUPLING FROM THE COMPANY VEHICLE. THE PUP TRAILER #1632 THEN ROLLED INTO THE DITCH, OIL LEAKED FROM THE DAMAGED TOP HATCH ON THE TRAILER, SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 5 BBLS OF CRUDE OIL ON THE GROUND. EMPLOYEE BROUGHT THE TRUCK TO COMPLETE STOP, HE THEN EXITED THE TRUCK AND WENT TO INSPECT PUP TRAILER #1362 THAT HAD COME UNCOUPLED FROM THE TRUCK #4101 AND ROLLED INTO THE DITCH. THE EMPLOYEE NOTED THAT CRUDE WAS SLOWLY LEAKING OUT OF THE TOP HATCH ON THE DAMAGED TRAILER. THE EMPLOYEE THEN MADE THE APPROPRIATE CALLS. THE BULK OF THE OIL THAT REMAINED IN THE PUP TRAILER WAS OFFLOADED TO ANOTHER PUP TRAILER TO ELIMINATE FURTHER SPILL DAMAGE. THE INITIAL SPILLED 5 BBLS OF CRUDE WERE ABLE TO BE RECOVERED FROM THE LOCATION OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: During a routine pre trip vehicle inspection a Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. driver noticed residue and leaking at the underside of the van trailer unit. The driver contacted dispatch and a response crew was summoned. Upon arrival the crew donned the proper PPE and unloaded the trailer to determine the source of the release. Upon identifying the source the crew overpacked the leaking drum into a properly rated salvage drum. All PPE and cleaning materials were also loaded into said drum and transported to the original disposal destination. The Illinois Emergency Management Agency was notified. Operator; John Neal, report #2014-0411.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the drums for transportation no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver, however, was re-instructed to conduct a thorough inspection of each container before acceptance and if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to either place the container into a suitable salvage drum, re containerize, or reject before transportation is initiated. In addition, the shipper was advised of the incident and instructed to verify the condition of all drums being offered for transportation.

2 totes containing a hazardous waste were picked up without incident.  When the driver arrived at the next stop he noticed a small leak and odor coming from the bottom valve of one of the totes.  He tightened the valve, cleaned up the leak and the leak appeared to have stopped.  Upon arrival at the intermediate truck transfer facility it was felt that the valve may still be leaking after looking at the spill pad.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and transfered the material into a new tote.  The state of Oklahoma was notified--incident number 141264.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility
column169: The tank test was well expired on this tote and it should not have been picked up.  The driver was disciplined for poor container selection.  The generator was notified not to load totes with expired tests.

column168: During an outbound BNSF train inspection in the railyard by BNSF carmen, entrained tank car DBUX 302638 was reported with wetness on its side shell. Immediate inspection by BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders revealed the closed 3 inch liquid valve was loose on its threaded connection which allowed commodity to escape at this valve's connection.  The responders tool tightened the liquid valve on its threaded connection two full turns which ended any further commodity release from this connection. Response was concluded by 1420 hrs. PDT, 4/30/2015.The spillage on DBUX 302638's shell rapidly evaporated. Intact shipper seal numbered 058908 at the valve housing cover was replaced by seal BNSF 06157925..

column168: ON 4-13-15 OUR DRIVER WAS STOPPED IN TRAFFIC. THERE HAS BEEN SOME TYPE OF INCIDENT UP AHEAD AND TRAFFIC WAS BACKED UP. OUR DRIVER DECIDED TO TURN RIGHT ONTO A SIDE STREET TO GO AROUND THE BACKED UP TRAFFIC. HE ATTEMPTED TO MAKE A SHARP RIGHT TURN @ APPROXIMATELY 5 MPH. AS HE MADE THE TURN, HIS TRAILER TIRES CUT ACROSS THE CORNER OF THE INTERSECTION. THE INSIDE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD WAS SOFT AND GAVE WAY AS THE TRAILER TIRES CROSSED OVER IT. AS THE SOFT SHOULDER GAVE WAY THE REAR END OF THE TRAILER STARTED SLIDE INTO THE DITCH CAUSING THE TRAILER TO ROLL ONTO ITS SIDE.  WHEN OUR DRIVER GOT OUR OF THE CAB, HE LOOKED AT THE TRAILER AND NOTICED PRODUCT DRIPPING FORM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE LOCATED NEAR THE DOME LID OF THE TANK.  THE PLACED A BUCKED UNDERNEATH THE VALVE TO CATCH THE DRIPPING PRODUCT HER THEN CALLED 911 TO REPORT THE ACCIDENT.
column169: TIDEPORT HAS CONDUCTED REMEDIAL TRAINING WITH THIS DRIVER COVERING PROPER TECHNIQUES FOR RIGHT HAND AND LEFT HAND TURNS.

column168: TUESDAY APRIL 28, 2015  TYSON THRASHER AND DAVE STREIN'S INVESTIGATION INTO THE SPILL AT COMPOSITES ONE ( GOSHEN, IN)    ON MONDAY AT APPROXIMATELY 09:30 MONDAY APRIL 20, 2015 WHILE UNLOADING A CARGO TANK (OWNED BY TRIMAC TRANSPORTATION) PRODUCT UN1866, RESIN SOLUTION, 2, III AOC PRODUCT NAME: H884-IVA-20 (POLYESTER RESIN SOLUTION)APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS OF RESIN WAS UNINTENTIONALLY RELEASED FROM A COMPOSITES ONE OWNED 2 INCH CAM LOCK FITTING HOSE CONNECTION. THE RELEASED PRODUCT RAN FROM THE PRESSURE SIDE OF COMPOSITES ONE OWNED PUMP DOWN TO A CATCH BASIN WHICH DRAINED INTO A PRIVATELY OWNED RETENTION AREA NORTH OF THE BUILDING. THE LEAK OCCURRED WHEN THE CARGO TANK WAS 3/4 EMPTY. BRIAN KOHRT (COMPOSITES ONE EMPLOYEE) WAS UNLOADING THE CARGO TANK WHEN HE NOTICED THE HOSE CONNECTION LEAKING.  HE SHUT THE PUMP DOWN, CLOSED ALL VALVES, DETERMINED THE PROBLEM.  HE IMMEDIATELY WENT TO CHECK THE DRAIN CLOSURE, OBSERVED IT WAS OPEN, AND SHUT IT.  NOTICING THE RESIN HAD MADE IT TO THE PRIVATELY OWNED RETENTION AREA, HE ADVISED HIS SUPERVISOR'S, TAMBI JONES.  SPILL CONTAINMENT AND CLEANUP WAS ONGOING BY COMPANY EMPLOYEES.  NANCY DEHMLOW (VP) CALLED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (202-267-2675) TO REPORT THE INCIDENT (NRC#1114162).  CALLS WERE ALSO MADE TO THE INDIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMNET (IDEM), OUR CONTACT WAS RICH HACKEL FORM IDEM (REPORT #54144) WHO ARRIVED ON SITE ABOUT AN HOUR LATER WITH GABE CAMERON FROM ELKHART COUNTY HEALTH DEPARTMENT GROUNDWATER PROGRAM SUPERVISOR.  WHILE WE REVIEWED THE SITUATION WITH THEM, NANCY DEHMLOW LOCATED ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION SERVICES, INC (ERS) OUT OF FT. WAYNE, IN. RICH HACKEL WAS FAMILIAR WITH THIS COMPANY AND APPROVING OF ERS TO REMEDIATE THE SITUATION. KYLE TURNER OF ERS ARRIVED 2 HOURS LATER AND DISCUSSED WITH RICH HACKEL WHAT WAS NEEDED TO REMEDIATE THE SITUATION.  THE PLAN WAS TO EXCAVATE THE SOIL, PLACE IN ROLL AWAY DUMPSTERS FOR DISPOSAL AND TEST REMAINING SOIL TO CONFIRM COMPLETE REMEDIATION WAS ACHIEVED. WE RECEIVED CONFIRMATION THE WEEK OF MAY 11 THAT THE SOIL TEST WAS CLEAN. CATCH BASIN AND DRAIN PIPES WERE ALSO CLEANED.    FINDINGS:  ROOT CAUSE:  A TWO INCH CAM LOCK FITTING GASKET MADE OF NITRILE/WHITE ON THE DISCHARGE SIDE (PRESSURE SIDE) FAILED ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO FLOW FROM THE CAM LOCK FITTING CONNECTION.  NITRILE IS NOT THE RIGHT ELASTOMER FOR THIS PRODUCT. STYRENE LIKE PRODUCTS WILL CAUSE NITRILE TO SHRINK AND GET BRITTLE. VITON B FLUOROELASTOMER (FKM) IS THE PROPER GASKET MATERIAL.  THE PUMP OFF AREA HAD AN AMPLE SUPPLY OF BOTH NITRILE (WHITE GASKETS) AND VITON B FLUOROELASTOMER (FKM). IN TALKING WITH DOUG HE FELT THE SUPPLIER MAY HAVE SHIPPED THE WRONG GASKETS (NITRILE) AT SOME POINT. CORRECTIVE ACTION: DOUG AND BRIAN WILL REMOVE ALL NITRILE GASKETS AND DISPOSE OF THEM ASSURING ONLY VITON GASKETS ARE USED GOING FORWARD. BRIAN WILL CHANGE OUT ALL HOSE GASKETS WEEKLY WITH NEW VITON GASKETS OR SOONER IF NEEDED.
column169: 1. THE CATCH BASIN (DRAIN) IN THE NEXT DOCK NORTH WHERE THE SPILLED PRODUCT MIGRATED TO WAS NOT SECURED. THE RUBBER MAT DESIGNED TO KEEP THE PRODUCT FROM ENTERING THE DRAIN (CATCH BASIN) HAD DETERIORATED OVER TIME AND WAS NOT CAPABLE OF KEEPING THE RESIN FOR ENTERING THE CATCH BASIN. CORRECTIVE ACTION: DOUG AND BRIAN WILL SECURE TWO NEW RUBBER MATS AND KEEP THIS CATCH BASIN COVERED AT ALL TIMES DURING THE UNLOADING OF RESIN CARGO TANKS.    2. THE SHUT OFF VALVE THAT CONTROLS THE FLOW FROM ALL THE DOCKS TO THE RETENTION AREA WAS IN THE OPEN POSITION. CORRECTIVE ACTION: DOUG AND BRIAN WILL KEEP THSI VALVE IN THE CLOSED POSITION AT ALL TIME EXPECT TO DRAIN STORM WATER.    3. TAMBI, DOUG AND BRIAN WILL UPDATE THE TANKER-UNLOADING SOP AND CHECKLIST TO ASSURE THESE CHANGES ARE INCLUDED IN THE POLICIES AND CHECKLISTS.    4. TYSON THRASHER (HSE SPECIALIST) AND TERRY KOLACKI TO PERFORM ZHA OR ADULT IN SUMMER OF 2015.

ON APRIL 22, 2015 AT APPROXIMATELY 5:30 AM, A UPS TRACTOR-TRAILER TRANSPORTING SEVERAL HUNDRED SMALL-PACKAGE SHIPMENTS, WAS INVOLVED IN A SINGLE-VEHICLE ACCIDENT. INCLUDED IN THE LOAD WERE FOUR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PACKAGES. THE VEHICLE, CONSISTING OF TRACTOR 265364 AND TRAILER 347783, LEFT THE ROADWAY AND OVERTURNED. IN THE COURSE OF THE ACCIDENT A FUEL TANK RUPTURED AND THE FUEL STARTED A FIRE THAT CAME TO INVOLVE THE TRAILER. A LOCAL VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT. AS IT BURNED THE TRAILER, THE FIRE CONSUMED MANY OF THE PACKAGES CONTAINED THEREIN, INCLUDING THE ISOPROPANOL SOLUTION REPORTED HERE. WHILE THE THREE REMAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE RECOVERED AFTER THE FIRE, NO SIGN OF THE ISOPROPANOL SOLUTION REMAINED IN THE DEBRIS.   UPS, INC. IS FILLING THIS REPORT ELECTRONICALLY IN ACCORDANCE WITH REQUIREMENT OF DOT-SP 15747. AS OF THIS DATE, THE POLICE DEPARTMENT AND FIRE DEPARTMENT REPORTS ARE NOT AVAILABLE.

Liquid was reported to be leaking from the B-end of the car and a vapor cloud was visible.  Inspection of the car revealed the tank cars liner had failed.  Temporary containment was placed under the car while waiting for transfer equipment and portable tanks to arrive on site for transfer of product. On arrival of equipment, product was transferred to portable tanks.  Upon completion of the transfer, the car was moved to an isolation track.  Product from the portable tanks was transferred into tank trucks, transported to consignee and off loaded.  The impacted area was remediated by flushing with a water/soda ash solution to neutralize the acid.  Temporary repairs will be made to the car to prevent release of any residual product while moving back to shop for repairs once an OTMA has been submitted by the shipper and approved by the FRA.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility. The bunghole cap was not compromised, but was replaced and securely tightened as a safe measure.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during transport and staging period so as to ensure the container(s) are on level surface when possible and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of leaking. IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required drum closure specifications.

column168: THE DRIVER TOOK HIS EYES OFF THE ROAD IN FRONT OF HIM FOR A SECOND, HIS RIGHT FRONT TIRE SLIPPED OFF THE PAVEMENT & THERE WAS A SOFT SHOULDER AND DITCH DROP OFF.  THE TRUCK WENT OVER ON ITS PASSENGER SIDE THEN ROLLED OVER ON ITS ROOF.  THE DRIVER, UNHURT, ROLLED DOWN HIS DRIVER'S WINDOW TO CRAWL OUT OF TRUCK.  A LADY WAS FOLLOWING BEHIND HIM & SHE CALLED 911 WITH EMERGENCY VEHICLES AND HAZMAT.  THE DRIVER ASSESSED THE SCENE AND NOTICED HE WAS LEAKING FUEL OUT BEFORE THE 911 CALL.  THE DRIVER THEN NOTIFIED HIS WORKPLACE.  ELLIE FUZZI, WHO IN TURN CALLED THE FOLLOWING, THE GENERAL MANAGER, ALLEN ROBINSON, PITKIN COUNTY DISPATCH, DERA, PERS, NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (REPORT #1115147), COLORADO HEALTH DEPT., OUR INSURANCE AGENT WITH KFSA (NATIONWIDE).  ALSO CALLED ECOS (ENVIRONMENTAL DISASTER & RESTORATION) COMPANY TO HELP US THRU.  THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE ER ROOM BY HIS WIFE AMBULANCE OK'D) JUST TO GET HIM CHECKED OUT FOR SURE AND A DRUG/ALCOHOL TEST.  THE HAZMAT TEAM CONTROLLED AND RESTRAINED THE SPILL THE BEST THEY COULD AND ECOS CLEANED UP.
column169: DISCUSS WITH ALL DRIVERS THE IMPORTANCE OF PULLING OVER FOR DISTRACTIONS AND ALWAYS BEING ALERT WITH THEIR  EYES ON THE ROAD AT ALL TIMES.    REITERATE HOW MUCH WORSE THIS COULD HAVE BEEN AND NONE OF IT WOULD BE WORTH LOSING A LIFE.

column168: Trace amounts of UN2809 mercury released from a submersible motor due to damage caused by a forklift. The release impacted an area of concrete dock floor measuring approximately 100' x 25'. The impacted area was decontaminated with a several applications of sulfur and water solution. The motor containing the material was drained of its entire contents and decontaminated with a sulfur and water solution. All material and generated waste was containerized in (55) gallon drums for disposal. All mercury vapor levels detected by the EPA on scene coordinator were below ATSDR HGVs 1999 EPA/IRIS industrial reoccupational standards.

column168: RIVER HAD JUST LOADED AND RETURNED TO PAVED COUNTY ROAD A SHORT DISTANCE PRIOR TO ACCIDENT AND HAD BEEN DRIVING LESS THAN 5 MINUTES. DRIVER CURVE ON COUNTY ROAD AT 50 MPH. DRIVER HAD BEEN AT ZERO THROTTLE FOR 16 SECONDS PRIOR TO ACCIDENT AND NEVER APPLIED BRAKES ON THE UNIT. VEHICLE LEFT THE ROADWAY TO THE RIGHT, STRUCK SEVERAL TREES AND THEN OVERTURNED ONTO ITS LEFT SIDE. THE DRIVER WAS KILLED BY BLUNT FORCE TRAUMA RESULTING FROM THE VEHICLE ROLLOVER. THE SHELL OF THE CARGO TANK WAS BREACHED DURING THE ROLLOVER EVENT WHEN A LARGE HOLE WAS TORN IN THE LEFT SIDE. THIS ALLOWED MOST OF THE LOAD OF OIL TO BE RELEASED ONTO THE RIGHT OF WAY. THE SOIL WAS VERY SANDY AT THE LOCATION AND THE OIL DID NOT MIGRATE ANY DISTANCE. BY THE TIME THE ACCIDENT WAS DISCOVERED, THE SITUATION WAS RELATIVELY STABLE WHICH LIMITED THE RESPONSE EFFORTS TO CLEAN-UP ONLY. ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED BY A CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR. NO WATER WAS IMPACTED AND THERE WAS NOT ANY FIRE AS A RESULT.
column169: WE HAVE BEEN UNABLE TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THIS ACCIDENT WITH ANY DEGREE OF CERTAINTY. THE DRIVER WAS VERY FAMILIAR WITH THE ROADWAY AND THE AREA. THE DRIVER HAD BEEN BEHIND THE WHEEL FOR ONLY A FEW MINUTES AFTER HAVING BEEN OUT OF THE TRUCK FOR A HALF HOUR WHILE LOADING. FATIGUE DOES NOT APPEAR TO HAVE BEEN A FACTOR. THE DRIVER HAD MORE THAN 20 YEARS EXPERIENCE HAULING CRUDE OIL IN TANKERS AND A GOOD SAFETY RECORD. STAND DOWN MEETINGS WERE HELD AND ADDITIONAL TRAINING HAS BEEN ADDED DURING THE REMAINDER OF THE YEAR.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION IS "CHLORINE TON" CONTAINER 81" LONG AND 31" IN DIAMETER. THE CONTAINER WAS SHIPPED TO OUR LOCATION TO BE CONDEMNED ACCORDING TO CFR 49 PART 180. THE CONTAINER IS MARKED "TO BE SCRAPPED" HAS A VACUUM". THE MARKING ON THE CONTAINER INDICATED THAT IT WAS "EMPTY" BUT NOT CLEANED.  THE CONTAINER WAS BEING PREPPED FOR CLEANING AND FLUSHING OF ANY RESIDUAL PRODUCT THAT MAY BE AS A RESULT OF PICKLING OF THE STEEL BY THE CHLORINE. THE EMPLOYEE HAD FILLED THE CONTAINER WITH WATER 24 HOURS PRIOR TO THE INCIDENT. THE EMPLOYEE THAT WAS WORKING ON THE UNIT WAS REMOVING A REAR SAFETY TO INSTALL A DRAIN LINE TO FLUSH THE WATER OUT OF THE UNIT. THE EMPLOYEE INDICATED THAT HE TESTED THE CONTAINER FOR PRESSURE/VACUUM. HE INDICATED THAT THERE WAS A VACUUM DETECTED. USING AN IMPACT WRENCH HE ATTEMPTED TO REMOVE THE REAR SAFETY. THE IMPACT WRENCH RELEASED THE SAFETY TO QUICKLY NOT ALLOWING HIM TO CHECK FOR ANY PRESSURE PRIOR TO REMOVING THE SAFETY. THE SAFETY WITH THE HELP OF THE PRESSURE AND THE IMPACT WRENCH RELEASED EXTREMELY QUICK, PREVENTING THE EMPLOYEE FROM RECOGNIZING THAT THE CONTAINER HAD PRESSURE.  THE RELEASE OF THE VAPOR TOOK APPROXIMATELY 15 MINUTES. THE VAPOR BEING HEAVIER THAN AIR AS HELP TO SPREAD WITH A AND PROCEEDED TO WIND OF APPROXIMATELY 10 KNOTS FORM THE NORTH WEST SPREADING THE CLOUD OF VAPOR OVER AN AREA APPROXIMATELY 50 SQ YARD.  THE HAZMAT TEAM INSTALLED THE PLUG TO SECURE THE CYLINDER.  THE CONTAINER AT THAT POINT WAS EMPTY FOR ANY RESIDUAL AT ATMOSPHERIC PRESSURE.
column169: ACTIONS THAT WILL BE TAKEN ARE TO IMPROVE THE PROCEDURES THAT OUTLINE THE PROPER METHOD TO TEST FOR PRESSURE/VACUUM.  THE PROCEDURE WILL BE IMPROVED AS FOLLOW:  1. ANY CONTAINER THAT IS INDICATED TO HAVE A "VACUUM" WILL BE TESTED FOR BOTH A VACUUM AS WELL AS FOR PRESSURE. A VACUUM TEST GAUGE WILL BE UTILIZED TO TEST FOR A VACUUM. THE SERIAL NUMBER OF THE UNIT WILL BE RECORDED WITH THE RESULTS OF THE TEST. WHETHER OR NOT A VACUUM IS DETECTED THE PRESSURE GAUGE WILL BE UTILIZED TO DETECT ANY PRESSURE. THIS WILL BE A DOUBLE INDICATION THAT THE VESSEL HAS NO PRESSURE AND THE VESSEL IN FACT HAS A VACUUM. THE PRESSURE WILL BE RECORDED AS INDICATED. IF THE UNIT HAS NO INDICATIONS OF A VACUUM OR PRESSURE THEN THE CUSTOMER WILL BE CONTACTED TO PICK UP THE CONTAINER AND HAVE IT RETURNED FOR A COMPLETE A PROPER VACUUM. IF THE CONTAINER HAS A POSITIVE INDICATION OF PRESSURE THEN IT WILL BE LABELED TO BE RETURNED TO THE CUSTOMER FOR PROPER EVACUATION.  2. IF ANY EMPLOYEE SUSPECTS THAT THE CONTAINER DOES NOT HAVE A PROPER AND COMPLETE VACUUM, E.G. AN ORDER FROM SLIGHT LEAK DUE TO A VALVE NOT BEING COMPLETELY SHUT, THEY ARE TO REJECT THE CONTAINER AS PER CGA C 6.0, AS IF IT WERE ANY OTHER CYLINDER TO BE PROCESSED. ITEM NUMBER "ONE" WILL BE PREFORMED IMMEDIATELY. THE OUTLINE WILL BE FOLLOWED FOR TESTING FOR VACUUM AND/OR PRESSURE.  3. THE METHOD OF REMOVAL OF ANY PLUG/SAFETY IN ORDER TO INSTALL A DRAIN WILL BE DONE WITH A HAND TOOL, E.G. A BREAKER BAR AND SOCKET ASSEMBLY, SO THAT THE OPERATOR CAN USE HIS SENSES MORE EFFECTIVELY.  LISTENING FOR ANY NOISE THAT WOULD INDICATE A PRESSURIZED CONTAINER AS WELL AS SMELL TO INDICATE AN ODOR THAT IS NOT NORMAL.

column42: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S., AT OR ABOVE 100 C AND BELOW ITS FLASH POINT (INCLUDING MOLTEN METALS, MOLTEN SALTS, ETC.)
column168: ON THE 14TH OF APRIL 2015 MR. WHITTEN A DILLON TRANSPORT, INC. EMPLOYEE ARRIVED AT THE MARIANI ASPHALT TO LOAD PG 76-22 ASPHALT TO BE DELIVERED TO RANGER CONSTRUCTION IN WINTER GARDEN, FL. THE DRIVER STAGED THE UNIT FOR LOADING IN THE SOUTH LOADING STATION, SECURED THE UNIT FOR LOADING, DON ALL OF THE REQUIRED PPE, OPENED THE DOME LID, SECURED THE LOADING SPOUT AND PROCEEDED TO LOAD PG 76-22 INTO THE CARGO TANK.  ONCE THE LOADING PROCESS WAS COMPLETED THE DRIVER FOR DILLON TRANSPORT, INC. SHUT THE LOADING PUMP OFF AND FAILED TO PROPERLY SECURE THE CUSTOMER VAVLE ON THE LOADING LINE. MR. WHITTEN REMOVED THE LOADING ARM PLACE A BUCKET UNDER THE LOADING SPOUT, CLOSED AND SECURED THE DOME LID FOR TRANSPORT. ONCE THE UNIT WAS SECURED MR. WHITTEN PROCEEDED TO EXIT
column169: THE DRIVER IN QUESTION RECEIVED REMEDIAL TRAINING ON THE PROCEDURE FOR LOADING AT THIS FACILITY. AN ADDITIONAL STEP HAS BEEN IMPLEMENTED INTO THE LOADING PROCESS WHERE THE DRIVER MUST WAIT AND VERIFY AND VERIFY ALL PRODUCT FLOW HAS BEEN STOPPED AND THERE IS NO RESIDUAL PRODUCT IN THE BUCKET UNDER THE LOADING SPOUT BEFORE EXITING THE LOADING RACK.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: UNIVAR DRIVER WAS MANEUVERING AN ELECTRIC PALLET JACK AT THE END OF HIS DRY, VAN TRAILER. ON THE PALLET WERE FOUR STRETCH WRAPPED STEEL DRUMS. AS THE DRIVER WAS TURNING THE PALLET JACK, ONE OF THE DRUMS RUBBED UP AGAINST A STRIKE-PLATE THAT IS PART OF THE LIFT GATE SYSTEM THUS COMPROMISING THE INTEGRITY OF THE DRUM (SLICING IT OPEN ABOUT A 1" GASH). THE DRIVER QUICKLY ATTEMPTED TO SLOW THE LEAK FROM THE DRUM AND PATCHED THE HOLE. SPILL ABSORBENT WAS PLACED OVER THE AMOUNT OF CHEMICAL WHICH SPILLED TO GROUND AND NRC ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED TO SUPPORT CLEAN UP EFFORTS. TOTAL OF 1.12 GALLONS SPILLED AFTER DRUM WAS WEIGHED TO VERIFY TOTAL RELEASE VOLUME.
column169: HAZARD RECOGNITION TRAINING WAS REVIEWED WITH DRIVER.  SPILL RESPONSE ACTIONS WERE HIGHLIGHTED AS QUICK ACTION PREVENTED THE RELEASE TO MINIMIZE TOTAL LOSS.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: TANKER TRUCK CARRYING NATURAL GAS CONDENSATE WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON KANSAS ROUTE 153 APPROACHING KANSAS ROUTE 61 SOUTHBOUND. ENTERING A CURVE IN THE ROADWAY, THE TRUCK LEFT ITS LANE AND WENT INTO THE MEDIAN. THE VEHICLE ROLLED ACROSS THE NORTHBOUND SIDE OF ROUTE 153 AND CAME TO REST IN THE DITCH TO THE SOUHTEAST (AND PARALLEL) OF THE ROAD AND NORTHWEST (AND PARALLEL) OF THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD TRACKS. THE TRUCK IMMEDIATELY CAUGHT FIRE AND WAS ENGULFED IN FLAMES, LEADING TO THE DEATH OF THE DRIVER.    WITHIN 20 MINUTES, POLICE FROM THE KANSAS HIGHWAY PATROL, ALONG WITH EMERGENCY MEDICAL AND FIRE RESPONDERS (CALLED THE CRITICAL HIGHWAY ACCIDENT RESPONSE TEAM, OR "CHART") WERE PRESENT AT THE ACCIDENT. THE FIRE AND HEAT WERE INTENSE AND PERSONNEL WAITED FOR THE NATURAL GAS PRESENT TO BURN OFF BEFORE INVESTIGATING THE SCENE. THE FIRE HAD DESTROYED ALMOST THE ENTIRE TANKER/TRAILER, LEAVING NO EVIDENCE OF THE LOCATION OF ANY INITIAL BREACH OR LEAK FROM THE TANK (SEE PHOTOS OF THE SCENE AND THE REMAINS OF THE TRAILER). THE DRIVER'S REMAINS WERE FOUND INSIDE THE CAB OF THE TRUCK.    IT IS ESTIMATED THAT, WHILE MUCH OF THE NATRUAL GAS CONDENSATE BURNED OR EVAPORATED AWAY DURING THE IMMEDIATE AFTERMATH OF THE ACCIDENT, NATURAL GAS/ETHANOL MAY BE PRESENT IN AN APPROXIMATELY 1,000 SQUARE FOOT AREA SURROUNDING THE ACCIDENT SITE.  THE CARRIER, WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF AN ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR, IS CURRENTLY IN THE MIDST OF CONDUCTING TESTS TO DETERMINE THE PRESENCE OF GASOLINE IN THE SOIL WHEREUPON IT WILL SEEK A STATE-SANCTIONED SOLUTION TO CLEAN UP THE AFFECTED GROUND.
column169: THE CARRIER IS CURRENTLY CONDUCTING THOROUGH INVESTIGATION OF THE INCIDENT TO DETERMINE IF THERE WERE ANY PROCEDURAL OR STRUCTURAL IRREGULARITIES ASSOCIATED WITH THE TRUCK, THE DRIVER, OR THE CARGO. AT THIS POINT, ANY CONCLUSIONS WOULD BE PRELIMINARY. THE CARRIER'S GOAL IS TO CONSTANTLY ENSURE THAT BEST PRACTICES WERE TAKEN BY ALL PARTIES INVOLVED IN SHIPPING OF PRODUCTS THROUGH ITS VEHICLES.

column168: On Wednesday 4/15/15 at appx 10:45 hours a GATX crew in the terminal noticed that GATX 75227 had ice forming on the side of the dome lid.  They notified terminal personnel and determined that a minor leak was the cause.  A crew from SWS Environmental was dispatched to make repairs.  They investigated the situation and determined that the liquid wheel valves on the liquid lines weren't seated correctly.  The crew opened and closed the valves several times with the plugs all the way in.  After doing this they bubble tested with soapy water and found no leaks.  The plugs were cleaned and new pipe tape was applied.  No further issues were detected.
column169: The crew opened and closed the valves several times with the plugs all the way in.  After doing this they bubble tested with soapy water and found no leaks.  The plugs were cleaned and new pipe tape was applied.  No further issues were detected.  Shipper was notified and the car was later emptied and released with no incident.

column168: A 330 gallon plastic IBC fell off forklift during unloading from shipping trailer. When the IBC made contact with the paved driveway, it cracked along the side of the container (approximately 2ft crack). Sulfuric Acid was released onto the paved driveway for approximately 1-3 minutes. Spill was contained with a combination of booms and sodium carbonate (soda ash). ACT Remedial Services was called promptly for clean up.
column169: Proper procedures for unloading and loading IBC shipping containers using a forklift was emphasized at company safety meeting. Additional alkaline neutralizers as well as containment booms were purchased.

column168: OUR DRIVER STATED WHEN HE BEGAN LOADING HE NOTICED ANHYDROUS AMMONIA ESCAPING INTO THE AIR. THE LOADING PROCESS WAS SHUT DOWN AND THE DRIVER CLOSED THE SPRAY FILL GLOBE VALVE. THE PRODUCT IN THE TRAILER WAS IMMEDIATELY PUMPED OFF. OUR DRIVER RETURNED THE EMPTY TRAILER TO OUR BETHANY LOCATION. NO BILL OF LADING WAS GENEARATED. THE TRAILER WAS LATER TAKEN TO GROWMARK TANK AND TRUCK CENTER IN PLEASANT HILL, IA. IT WAS DISCOVERED THE SPRAY FILL QUARTER TURN BLEEDER VALVE WAS OPEN. THE STOP PEG WAS BENT ALLOWING THE VALVE TO OPEN WHEN TURNED TO FAR. A NEW VALVE WAS INSTALLED, I RECEIVED AN EMAIL FROM KOCH INDUSTRIES ON 6-12-15 STATING THEY ESTIMATED 9.12 POUNDS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED OVER A 3.13 MINUTE DURATION.  THIS WAS NOT A FOR HIRE MOVE. WE TRANSPORT ANHYDROUS AMMONIA FROM KOCH INDURSTRIES TO OUR RETAIL LOCATIONS.
column169: OUR DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO VISUALLY CHECK ALL VALVES AS PART OF THEIR PRE-TRIP.

column58: Loading or Unloading Lines; Tank Shell
column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Rollover Accident
column168: CMTV ROLLOVER AT EKMAN, W.V. RT 52 NORTH. SHELL OF CMTV WAS TORN OPEN IN 3 PLACES.  APPROX SIZE SILVER DOLLAR AT EACH FAILURE.  2 LOCATED 3/4 UP ON LEFT SIDE OF CMTV AND 1 ON RIGHT SIDE AT 1/2 WAY POINT.  ALL 3 AT 1ST BULKHEAD BETWEEN COMPARTMENTS 1&2.  THIS ALLOWED FOR GASOLINE TO LEAK OUT OF CMTV.  LOADING AND UNLOADING LINES UNDERNEATH CMTV WERE CRUSHED, ALLOWING GASOLINE TO LEAK FROM THEM.  LOCAL MINING COMPANY MOVED EQUIPMENT TO SITE IMMEDIATELY TO DIG A TRENCH AND CONTAIN SPILL TO PREVENT GASOLINE GOING INTO WATER WAY.  NO GASOLINE WENT INTO ANY WATERWAY.  R.T. ROGERS LOCAL EQUIPMENT ARRIVED ON SCENE TO EVACUATE REMAINING GASOLINE FROM CMTV.  W.E.L. EMERGENCY RESPONSE GROUP WAS ALSO ON SCENE TO RECOVER EXCESS STANDING GASOLINE ON SOIL AND START REMEDIATION PROCESS IMMEDIATELY.  APPROXIMATE RESPONSE TIME TO BEGIN CONTAINMENT WAS 30 MINUTES OR LESS FROM MINING CO. 10-15 MINUTES FOR FIRE, POLICE, EMS, 35 MINUTES FROM R.T. ROGERS OIL CO EMPLOYEES. 45 MINUTES FOR W.E.L.
column169: CURRENTLY, WE ARE TRACKING OUR CMTV'S WITH THE USE OF FLEET MATES REVEAL.  GPS REAL TIME TRACKING.  THIS MONITORS DRIVERS HABITS, LOADING/UNLOADING TIMES, HOURS OF SERVICE ETC. WE HAVE STEPPED UP OUR SAFETY MEETING AND TRAINING PROCEDURES ALONG WITH PLACING SAFETY BULLETINS AT OUR TIME CLOCKS AND ARE HAVING OUR DRIVERS READ AND SIGN THAT THEY HAVE ROAD AND UNDERSTOOD THE BULLETINS.  FEDERATED INSURANCE HAS SUPPLIED VIDEO HELPS TO CONTINUE OUR SAFETY AWARENESS PROGRAM.  HEIGHTENED AWARENESS FOR ALL CMTV DRIVERS, OWNER, OPERATORS IS ESSENTIAL TO ALL PUBLIC SAFETY ON OUR NATIONS HIGHWAYS.  WE WOULD LIKE TO SEE ADDITIONAL TRAINING BEGIN AT OUR HIGH SCHOOL LEVEL STUDENTS TO EDUCATE THEM TO WEIGHTS OF CMTV'S, STOPPING DISTANCES, ROOM TO GET AROUND, JUDGING CMTV SPEEDS, PASSING/FOLLOWING CMTV'S ETC.

column168: AT NIGHT ON APRIL 18TH 2015 OUR DRIVER, DOUMBIA MOUSSA, WENT TO GAS STATION AT 610 CENTRAL AVE TO DELIVER THE GASOLINE.  TO DELIVER THE FUEL HE FITTED THE PIPE TO UNDERGROUND FUEL TANK.  POSSIBLY THE PIPE FITTING WAS LOOSE AND DRIVER DID NOT DOUBLE CHECK IT. HE RELEASED THE GAS THAT CAUSED A MINOR SPILL. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED ON THE SPOT IMMEDIATELY BY THE CUSTOMER AND FIRE DEPARTMENT REACHED THERE AND FUEL SPILL WAS CLEANED UP. ON APRIL 20TH, 2015 CSC WAS CALLED BY THE OWNER OF THE GAS STATION TO CLEAN UP THE SITE. CSC CLEANED UP ALL THE AREA.  (REPORT OF CSC IS ATTACHED WITH THIS FORM). CSC HAD ALREADY REQUESTED THE CLOSURE OF SPILL MATTER.  BILL OF LADING AND DELIVERY PAPERS ARE ALSO ATTACHED WITH THIS FORM.
column169: THE DRIVER WAS WARNED TO BE CAREFUL IN FUTURE AND HE TOOK SAFETY CLASSES FOR ONE WEEK FORM THE SAFETY MANAGER.  AND ALL OTHER DRIVERS WERE GIVEN INSTRUCTIONS TO BE CAREFUL IN FUTURE.

column25: ISLAND OAK LLC DBA ISLAND PETROLEUM SERVICES
column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: THE VEHICLE WAS PICKED UP FROM THE MECHANIC IN ANACORTES.  IT HAD RECEIVED ITS ANNUAL TANK INSPECTION AND DOT INSPECTIONS/REPAIRS.  THE TRUCK WAS TAKEN TO THE REFINERY AND THEN TO THE BARGE TO GO TO ORCAS ISLAND.  THE TRUCK WAS THEN DRIVEN TO THE "SAFE HOUSE" YARD FOR STORAGE.  THE DRIVER DETACHED THE GLAD HANDS FROM THE TRAILER AND RAISED THE DRAW BAR.  THERE WAS NO MOVEMENT ONCE HITCH WAS CLEARED.  THIS INDICATES BRAKES ARE SET.  SAFETY CHAINS WERE REMOVED.  THE DRIVER GOT UP TO GET THE CHALKS STORED ON THE TRACTOR PORTION.  SECONDS LATER THE TRAILER STARTED TO ROLL BACK.  IT CONTINUED TO ROLL DOWN A SMALL BACK (6 TO 8 FEET).  AT THE BOTTOM THE TRAILER ROLLED 3/4 AROUND AND CAME TO REST ON ITS SIDE.  THE DRIVER CALLED 911.  FUEL STARTED TO LEAK OUT OF ONE OF THE VENT PORTS ON THE TOP (ABOUT A QUART A MINUTE OR LESS).  NO LEAKS FROM THE TANK STRUCTURE.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DID NOT ALLOW MY DRIVER TO GET NEAR THE VEHICLE TO PUT PUTTY IN THE VENT TO STOP THE LEAK.  FROM THIS POINT THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DID NOT ALLOW US TO STOP THE LEAK EVEN THOUGH WE HAD THE MEANS TO.  WE COULD HAVE STOPPED THE LEAK WITH A POTENTIAL OF ONLY HAVING SPILLED 5 TO 10 GALLONS.  THE ROLL OVER OCCURRED AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30.  NRC WAS CALLED AND THEY ARRIVED ONSITE AT 9:30 (IT'S HARD TO GET TO AN ISLAND).  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED BY THEM IN THE SAME MANNER AS WAS DESCRIBED BY OUR COMPANY 7 HOURS PRIOR.  NRC DRILLED HOLES IN THE SIDE OF THE TANK AND REMOVED ALL BUT 280 GALLONS PICKED UP AT REFINERY.  THAT IS HOW WE KNOW MUCH FUEL WAS LEAKED.  THE FUEL WAS TRANSFERRED TO DONOR TRUCK.  THE EFFECTED EARTH WAS DUG UP AND STORED IN A PLASTIC TARPED AREA AND COVERED UNTIL THE SOIL WAS SHIPPED OFFSITE AND TREATED.
column169: OWNER OF ISLAND PETROLEUM SERVICES ORDERED AN INDEPENDENT INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER. THE FAILURE OCCURRED WITH THE CHECK VALVE LEADING TO A RESERVE TANK ON TRAILER. THE FAILURE OCCURRED AT 10 SECONDS FOLLOWING REMOVAL OF THE GLAD HANDS.  THIS PHENOMENON WAS REPEATED SEVERAL TIMES AND FILMED. THE FLOOD OF AIR RELEASED THE BRAKES. IT IS MY UNDERSTANDING THIS CHECK VALVE IS NOT PART OF A ROUTINE DOT INSPECTION. OUR NEW COMPANY POLICY IS TO REPLACE THE CHECK VALVE EVERY FIVE YEARS REGARDLESS OF PERFORMANCE. I HAVE SHARED THIS ADVICE WITH MY LOCAL COMPETITORS WHO HAVE SIMILAR TRUCKS. WE ARE IN A SALT WATER ENVIRONMENT SO PARTS CAN FAIL FASTER THAN IN OTHER PARTS OF THE COUNTRY.    THE "SAFE HOUSE" SITE WILL HAVE ECOLOGY BLOCKS PLACED AT THE TOP OF THE EMBANKMENT. THE GRADE WAS RECENTLY REDONE AND IT APPEARS FLAT BUT THE GRADE IS MISLEADING AS IT DOES PITCH TOWARD THE EMBANKMENT. THE CONCRETE BARRIER WILL PREVENT ANY ROLLING VEHICLE OR MISJUDGED DISTANCES WHEN BACKING A VEHICLE.    IT IS ALSO COMPANY POLICY TO CHALK WHEELS NO MATTER WHERE THE VEHICLE RESTS.  WE ARE NOURISHING THIS AS HABIT.

column168: THE INCIDENT WAS A TRAFFIC ACCIDENT SINGLE VEHICLE TANKER, AS A RESULT OF DRIVER BEING UNDER THE INFLUENCE OF ALCOHOL. THE TRUCK RAN OFF THE ROAD, DOWN SIDE OF DITCH, BACK UP AN EMBANKMENT, HIT A POWER POLE THEN ROLLED OVER, FUEL WAS IN THE MIDDLE COMPARTMENT. THE DOME LID BEGAN TO LEAK SLOWLY SAND AND OIL ABSORBANTS WERE USED TO PREVENT THE GAS FROM SOAKING INTO THE GROUND. THE LID LEAKED A SLOW DRIP FOR APPROXIMATELY 3 HOURS BEFORE THE ENVIRONMENTAL CREW SLOWED UP AND VACUUMED IT OUT. THE ENVIRONMENTAL TEAM THEN CLEANED UP BY EXCAVATING ETC.
column169: ALCOHOL AND DRUG USE HAS BEEN TOPICS OF SEVERAL DRIVER MEETINGS.  RANDOM DRUG AND ALCOHOL TESTS ARE PERFORMED ON REGULAR BASIS.  ROLL OVER VIDEOS HAVE BEEN PRESENTED.

column168: While in transit on a highway and traveling at a rate of speed of approximately of 55 mph, our vehicle came in contact with a third party vehicle who lost control of their vehicle due to unsafe speed for conditions (rainy and dark).  Reporting party lost control as a result of making head on contact with the responsible party, resulting in the tank vehicle to rollover and slide along the asphalt.  As a result, the aluminum tank was punctured, allowing for product to be released. The flow of product went into an empty cement canal that was self-contained and did not have any entry or exit to a storm drain or water way. Emergency responders were called to the scene in which the tank was plugged and the drain was diked.
column169: Drivers were trained and reminded that adverse reactions such as trying to avoid an accident are to be avoided in order to prevent rollover accidents.  While this particular accident was primarily non-preventable due to another vehicle entering the pathway of the reporting party, defensive driving techniques such as holding one's lane was re-trained to all drivers.

column168: THE ACCIDENT WAS NOT A PACKAGE FAILURE BUT AN EQUIPMENT. THE AXEL APPEARED TO HAVE SNAPPED OFF PARALLEL TO THE RIM IN WHAT APPEARED TO A CLEAN FRACTURE. WE HAVE CONTINUED TO MAINTAIN OUR MAINTENANCE PROGRAM, AND ALWAYS LOOKING FOR OPPORTUNITIES FOR IMPROVEMENT.
column169: OUR MAINTENANCE PROGRAM HAS BEEN SET UP SINCE G&G OPENED ITS DOOS. G&G TRANSPORT HAS GOTTEN STRICT BY NOT ALLOWING VARIOUS TECHNICIANS INSPECT AND WORK ON OUR EQUIPMENT. WE CONTACTED ONE MECHANIC TO MAINTAIN AND INSPECT OUR VEHICLE. WE CONTINUE TO WORK STRONG AND HARD TO KEEP EQUIPMENT SAFE WHEN OUT ON OUR PUBLIC AND PRIVATE HIGHWAYS.

Flight 4010 landed at Richmond Airport.  Upon landing a loose lithium battery in a passenger's carry-on bag ignited when it made contact with loose coins in the carry-on bag. The bag was located under seat 2D.  The battery burned out of the bag and burned the carpet.    The flight attendant extinguished the flame with a portable fire extinguisher and due to smoke the crew did an emergency evacuation on taxiway BRAVO.
column169: Require spare batteries for e-cigarettes to be packaged properly.  If the battery was packaged properly and not left loose the battery would not have made contact with the loose change and the fire would not have taken place.

column168: ECO-ENERGY TRANSPORTATION HAD A TRACTOR TRAVELING NORTHWEST ON BRINGLE FERRY RD IN SALISBURY, NC AFTER LOADING ETHANOL AT OUR LOADING FACILITY IN DENTON, NC. AT APPROXIMATELY 6:45AM CST, THE TRACTOR DEPARTED THE ROAD ON THE PASSENGER'S SIDE.  THE TRACTOR ROLLED OVER TO THE PASSENGER SIDE, STRIKING THE GROUND, AND THEN ROLLED ONTO THE DRIVER'S SIDE OF THE TRACTOR WHERE IT CAME TO REST. THIS WAS 11540 BRINGLE FERRY RD. NO OTHER PEOPLE WERE INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT. THE DRIVER WAS KILLED IN THE INCIDENT. THE COLLISION ALSO RESULTED IN THE TRAILER BEING COMPROMISED AND A LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 3800 GALLONS OF ETHANOL.    THERE WERE TWO EYE WITNESSES THAT INDICATED THE RATE OF SPEED AND DRIVING ALL SEEMED APPROPRIATE. DPS HAS CONFIRMED THAT SPEED WAS NOT A FACTOR IN THIS INCIDENT. INITIAL CAUSE OF DEATH FOR THE DRIVER WAS RULED TO BE BLUNT FORCE TRAUMA TO THE HEAD.
column169: IN RELATION TO THE CRASH:    THE EXISTING EVIDENCE INDICATES THE CRASH LIKELY RESULTED FROM INATTENTION.  INATTENTION, AS WE KNOW, COULD RESULT FROM A VARIETY OF CAUSATION FACTORS INCLUDING, BUT NOT LIMITED TO, FATIGUE, IN-CAB DISTRACTIONS, OUTSIDE INFLUENCES, SICKNESS, ETC., OR A COMBINATION OF THESE OR SIMILAR FACTORS.  OUR CORPORATE RESPONSE TO MODIFYING DRIVER BEHAVIOR AND/OR PROVIDING COUNTERMEASURE EDUCATION AND TRAINING INCLUDE:    *  UTILIZING EXISTING METRIC DATA TO DETERMINE DRIVER BEHAVIOR JUST BEFORE AND DURING INCIDENTS (AS WELL AS KNOWN NEAR MISSES), DETERMINING IF AND WHERE DEFICIENCIES EXIST, AND REMEDIATING DEFICIENCIES VIA THE MOST EFFECTIVE MEANS    *  PROVIDING PROFESSIONAL (DEFENSIVE) DRIVING EDUCATION/TRAINING TO DRIVERS AS WELL AS REQUIRING THE SAME EDUCATION/TRAINING FOR NEW-HIRES (WITH ADDITIONAL FOCUS ON THE PROPER RESPONSE AND CORRECTIVE STEERING AFTER DROPPING A WHEEL OFF THE SHOULDER OR RUNNING OFF ON THE SHOULDER OF A ROADWAY)    *  ENSURING THE COMPANY DESIGNATES AND ENFORCES THE MOST APPROPRIATE AND SAFE ROADWAY ROUTES FOR OUR EQUIPMENT TRAVEL    *  PROVIDING WELLNESS INFORMATION AND FATIGUE RECOGNITION AND COUNTERMEASURE EDUCATION TO OUR DRIVERS AND OPERATIONS STAFF    *  CONDUCTING SAFETY MEETINGS AND USE OTHER COMMUNICATIONS MEANS WITH OUR DRIVERS TO DISCUSS THIS TRAGIC INCIDENT AND THE POTENTIAL CONSEQUENCES OF INATTENTION AND/OR MAKING WRONG DECISIONS    IN RELATION TO THE RESPONSE AND REMEDIATION OF THE RELEASE:    IMMEDIATELY UPON NOTIFICATION OF THE EVENT, LOCAL FIRE, EMS, AND A HAZMAT RESPONSE COMPANY (HEPACO) WHERE CONTACTED TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE.  TWO LOCAL RESIDENTS WERE EVACUATED FROM THEIR HOME TO AVOID ANY FURTHER ISSUES IN THE EVENT THAT THE INCIDENT BECAME WORSE.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD CONTROL OF THE SCENE FOR THE FIRST SEVERAL HOURS TO APPLY FOAM AND WATER TO THE CRASH.    ONCE SAFE, THE TANKER WAS DRILLED AND THE REMAINING HAZMAT WAS REMOVED AND HEPACO BEGAN TAKING STEPS TO MITIGATE ANY FURTHER MIGRATION OF THE CONTAMINANTS.    SINCE THE DATE OF THE SPILL, THROUGH THE ACTIONS OF HEPACO, WE HAVE TAKEN SEVERAL STEPS TO REMEDIATE THE IMPACTED AREA.  AS OF TODAY, REMEDIATION EFFORTS ARE STILL ONGOING.  WE WILL FILE A SUPPLEMENTAL REPORT WITH THE FULL DETAILS OF ALL REMEDIATION UPON COMPLETION.

column17: JP LIQUIDS, LLC DBA JP ENERGY
column168: FOY WALLACE, BILL WEBB AND DEBORAH KRYAK (JPEP) DEPARTED DENTON AIRPORT AT APPROXIMATELY 1130 ON 4/23/15.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE, AT APPROXIMATELY 1030 THERE WAS A CONFERENCE CALL WITH THE HAZMAT CHIEF AT THE SCENE, CHIEF ADDISON.  JPEP ADVISED A DEFENSIVE POSTURE BE RESPONDERS UNTIL JPEP COULD ARRIVE ON SCENE TO ASSIST IN DETERMINATION OF A PROPER WAY TO RESOLVE PROPANE REMAINING ON DAMAGE TRAILER.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE ACCIDENT SCENE, APPROXIMATELY 1300, INCIDENT COMMAND WAS ESTABLISHED SOUTH OF 2102 LUBBOCK ROAD BROWNFIELD, TEXAS ON THE NORTH BOUND SIDE OF LUBBOCK ROAD, NORTH  OF THE INTERSECTION OF LEVELLAND ROAD AND LUBBOCK ROAD.  JP LIQUIDS TRACTOR/TRAILER 7079/8070 DETACHED FROM THE TRACTOR WHICH WAS LAYING ON THE DIVER SIDE EAST OF THE FRONT SECTION OF THE TRAILER.  TRANSAMERICA TRACTOR/REFRIGERATED TRAILER WAS BURNED LOCATED IN THE MEDIAN OF LUBBOCK ROAD WITH THE TRACTOR POINTED INTO THE SOUTH BOUND LANES OF LUBBOCK ROAD.  STATE POLICE REPORTED THAT THE TRANSAMERICA TRUCK HAD ATTEMPTED A "U TURN AFTER MISSING HIS STOP."  THE REAR OF HTE TRANSAMERICA TRAILER APPEARED TO HAVE SIGNS OF AN IMPACT ON THE DRIVER SIDE REAR OF THE TRAILER, APPROXIMATELY 5-8 FEET FROM THE END OF THE TRAILER.  DOOR HINGES THAT APPEARED TO BE FROM THE REAR OF THE TRANSAMERICA TRAILER WERE LOCATED AT THE EDGE OF THE SLOW LANE OF THE NORTH BOUND TRAFFIC NEAR THE EAST SIDE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD WHICH WOULD INDICATE THAT POINT OF IMPACT HAPPENED NEAR THE EDGE OF THE SHOULDER AS ROBERT TOOK EVASIVE ACTION TOWARD THE EAST EDGE OF THE ROAD.  FIRE DEPARTMENT EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE ON THE TRAILER, AND THE COUNTY SHERIFF EVACUATED THERMO-FLUIDS, GEBO'S, TEXAS HERB, AND RESIDENTIAL HOUSE ALONG BALLARD ST. AND BYNUM RD.  THE SHERIFF WAS NOT ABLE TO GIVE A HEAD COUNT ON THE NUMBER OF PEOPLE EVACUATED, THE NUMBERS REPORTED ARE ESTIMATED.
column169: ROBERT MELVIN DID EVERYTHING POSSIBLE TO AVOID THE COLLISION.  THIS INCIDENT DOES NOT APPEAR TO BE PREVENTABLE ON BEHALF OF THE JPE DRIVER.

column168: A DELIVERY OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE WAS BEING MADE TO THE PEEKSKILL MIDDLE SCHOOL. THE DRIVER AND TRAINEE THEN MET WITH THE SCHOOL CUSTODIAN TO ENSURE PROPER MATERIAL AND GALLONS TO BE DELIVERED. SLACK EMPLOYEE’S THEN HOOKED UP ALL CONNECTIONS TO BEGIN PUMP OFF. WHEN THE DESIRED AMOUNT WAS REACHED, VALVES WERE SHUT AND AIR WAS INTRODUCED TO THE PRODUCT LINE TO CLEAN IT. THEN A POP WAS HEARD AND BLEACH BEGAN TO SPRAY FROM THE TOP OF THE TRUCK. UNTIL PRESSURE HAD BLED OFF THE TANK IT COULDN’T BE STOPPED. APPROXIMATELY 40-60 GALLONS HAD ESCAPED FROM THE BULK TANK INTO THE PARKING LOT.
column169: UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A BALL VALVE FAILED AT THE MANUFACTURED SEEM. A NEW VALVE WAS INSTALLED AND PIPING HAD BEEN TESTED AS WELL. BEGGING THE PROCESS OF MANUFACTURE RECOMMENDATIONS AS TO BEST PRACTICE FOR REPLACEMENT WITH PUC VALVE EXPOSED TO THE ELEMENT AND ALSO RESEARCH TO SEE IF THE VALVE IN QUESTION WAS OF A DEFECTED BATCH.
